{{Infobox Hurricane | Name=Tropical Depression Ten | Type=Tropical Depression | Year=2005 | Basin=Atl | Image location=Tropical Depression 10 (2005).png | Image name=Tropical Depression Ten | alt=Satellite image of elliptical cloud pattern with no clear center | Formed=August 13, 2005 | Dissipated=August 14, 2005 | 1-min winds=30 | Pressure=1008 | Damages=None | Inflated= | Fatalities=None reported | Areas=None | Hurricane season=[[2005 Atlantic hurricane season]] }} '''Tropical Depression Ten''' was the tenth [[tropical cyclone]] of the record-breaking [[2005 Atlantic hurricane season]]. It formed on August 13 from a [[tropical wave]] that emerged from the west coast of Africa on August 8. As a result of strong [[wind shear]], the depression remained weak and did not strengthen beyond tropical depression status. The cyclone degenerated on August 14, although its remnants partially contributed to the formation of Tropical Depression Twelve, which eventually intensified into [[Hurricane Katrina]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff Writer|title=Capt. Julie Reports On Hurricane Katrina|date=June 5, 2007|publisher=''WPTV''|accessdate=2009-06-26|url=http://www.wptv.com/content/chopper5/story/Capt-Julie-Reports-On-Hurricane-Katrina/q__v8S2TZES2GiccRTQ2bw.cspx}}</ref> The cyclone had no effect on land, and did not directly result in any fatalities or damage.
== Meteorological history == {{storm path|10-L 2005 track.png|alt=Track map of tropical depression}} On August 8, a [[tropical wave]] emerged from the west coast of Africa and entered the Atlantic Ocean. Tracking towards the west, the depression began to exhibit signs of [[Atmospheric convection|convective organization]] on August 11. The system continued to develop, and it is estimated that Tropical Depression Ten formed at 1200 UTC on August 13. At the time, it was located about {{convert|1600|mi|km}} east of [[Barbados]].<ref name="TCR"/> Upon its designation, the depression consisted of a large area of thunderstorm activity, with curved [[tropical cyclone#Physical structure|banding features]] and expanding [[outflow (meteorology)|outflow]]. However, the environmental conditions were predicted to quickly become unfavorable.<ref>{{cite web|author=Avila|title=Tropical Depression Ten Discussion Number 1|date=August 13, 2005|publisher=National Hurricane Center|accessdate=2009-01-21|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2005/dis/al102005.discus.001.shtml?}}</ref> The depression moved erratically and slowly towards the west, and [[wind shear]] inhibited any significant intensification. Late on August 13, it was "beginning to look like [[Hurricane Irene (2005)|Irene]]-junior as it undergoes southwesterly mid-level shear beneath the otherwise favorable upper-level outflow pattern".<ref name="disc2"/> The wind shear was expected to relent within 48 hours, prompting some forecast models to suggest the depression would eventually attain hurricane status.<ref name="disc2">{{cite web|author=Stewart|title=Tropical Depression Ten Discussion Number 2|date=August 13, 2005|publisher=National Hurricane Center|accessdate=2008-01-21|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2005/dis/al102005.discus.002.shtml?}}</ref>
By early August 14, the shear had substantially disrupted the storm, leaving the low-level [[atmospheric circulation|center of circulation]] exposed from the area of convection, which was also deteriorating. After meandering, the storm began to move westward. Forecasters expected it to resume a northwestward track as [[high pressure area|high pressure]] to the south of [[Bermuda]] was forecasted to weaken and another high was predicted to form southwest of the [[Azores]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Knabb|title=Tropical Depression Ten Discussion Number 3|date=August 14, 2005|publisher=National Hurricane Center|accessdate=2009-01-21|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2005/dis/al102005.discus.003.shtml?}}</ref> By 1800 UTC on August 14, the strong shear had further weakened the storm, and it no longer met the criteria for a tropical cyclone. It degenerated into a remnant low, and the National Hurricane Center issued their final advisory on the cyclone. Moving westward, it occasionally produced bursts of convective activity, before dissipating on August 18.<ref name="TCR"/>
Tropical Depression Twelve formed over the southeastern [[Bahamas]] at 2100 UTC on August 23, partially from the remains of Tropical Depression Ten.<ref>{{cite book|page=61|url=http://books.google.com/?id=-a8DRl1HuwoC&q=%22tropical+depression+ten%22+2005&dq=%22tropical+depression+ten%22+2005|author=United States Senate|title=Hurricane Katrina: a nation still unprepared|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|year=2006|isbn=0-16-076749-0}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Michael P. Erb|title=A Case Study of Hurricane Katrina: Rapid Intensification in the Gulf of Mexico|year=|publisher=University of North Carolina Asheville|accessdate=2009-06-26|url=http://facstaff.unca.edu/chennon/research/documents/erb_ncur2006_preprint.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref> While the normal standards for numbering tropical depressions in the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] stipulate that the initial designation be retained when a depression regenerates, satellite imagery indicated that a second [[tropical wave]] had combined with Tropical Depression Ten north of [[Puerto Rico]] to form a new, more complex weather system, which was then designated as Tropical Depression Twelve.<ref>{{cite web | author = Stewart, Stacy | publisher = [[National Hurricane Center]] | url = http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/archive/2005/dis/al122005.discus.001.shtml | title = Tropical Depression Twelve Discussion Number 1 | date=August 23, 2005 | accessdate = 2009-01-21}}</ref> In a re-analysis, it was found that the low-level circulation of Tropical Depression Ten had completely detached and dissipated; only the remnant mid-level circulation moved on and merged with the second tropical wave. As a result, the criteria for keeping the same name and identity were not met. Tropical Depression Twelve later became [[Hurricane Katrina]].<ref name="KatrinaTCR"/> [[File:TD 10 August 13, 2005.jpg|right|thumb|Tropical Depression Ten on August 13|alt=Satellite image of elliptical cloud pattern with no clear center]]
== Impact == Because Tropical Depression Ten never approached land as a [[tropical cyclone]], no [[tropical cyclone watches and warnings]] were issued for any land masses. No effects, damages, or fatalities were reported, and no ships reported tropical storm-force winds in association with the depression. The system did not attain tropical storm status; as such, it was not given a name by the [[National Hurricane Center]].<ref name="TCR">{{cite web|author=Jack Beven|title=Tropical Depression Ten Tropical Cyclone Report|date=January 17, 2006|publisher=National Hurricane Center|accessdate=2009-01-21|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/pdf/TCR-AL102005_Ten.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref> The storm partially contributed to the formation of Hurricane Katrina, which became a [[List of Category 5 Atlantic hurricanes|Category 5]] hurricane on the [[Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Scale]] and made landfall in [[Louisiana]], causing catastrophic damage. Katrina was the costliest [[North Atlantic tropical cyclone|hurricane]], and one of the five deadliest, in the history of the United States.<ref name="KatrinaTCR"> {{cite web|last=Knabb|first=Richard D|coauthors=Rhome, Jamie R.; Brown, Daniel P|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/pdf/TCR-AL122005_Katrina.pdf|format=PDF|title=Tropical Cyclone Report: Hurricane Katrina: 23–30 August 2005|publisher=National Hurricane Center|date=December 20, 2005; updated August 10, 2006|accessdate=2009-01-21}}</ref>
